      <h1> Interactive Media : Assignment 1 </h1>

      <h2> Chosen Web Project: National Gallery of Victoria </h2>

<p1> <a href="https://www.ngv.vic.gov.au/"> NGV website </a> <br><br> </p1>


<p1> 1. What was the first thing you paid attention to when interacting with the experience? <br><br> </p1>
<p2>
  The acknowledgement of the traditional owners for the land on which the NGV was built <br>
  Once on the home page, it was the scrolling gallery at the header. <br><br> 
</p2>

<p1> 2. Spend two minutes with the experience and create a list of each of your discrete actions. <br><br> </p1>
<p2>
  - Scrolled through the displayed exhibitions and events <br>
  - Went to the "Collection" page using the nav bar <br>
  - Clicked on the "Takahiro Iwasaki" collection <br>
  - Clicked through the image collection <br>
  - Went back to the "What's On" page through the nav bar <br>
  - Clicked on "see all exhibitions" <br>
  - Scrolled through the page until I reached the footer <br>
  - Clicked on "Virtual Tours" <br>
  - Went back to the home page after browsing the displayed tours <br><br> 
</p2>

<p1> 3. What part of the experience did you spend the most time engaging with? <br><br> </p1>
<p2>
  Viewing the photo collections that linked to pages containing further information <br><br> 
</p2>

<p1> 4. What was the most common action in your two minute interaction with the experience? <br><br> </p1>
<p2>
  Scrolling or using the nav bar to navigate the site <br><br> 
</p2>

<p1> 5. What is your impression of the intended primary goal of the interactive experience? <br><br> </p1>
<p2>
  To show off all the avaliablee exhibitions and events (past, present and upcoming) and provide extra detail on each <br><br> 
</p2>

<p1> 6. How does the interactive experience communicate this primary goal? <br><br> </p1>
<p2>
  Very smoothly and efficiently, with clear grids and collections that are appropriately lablled <br><br> 
</p2>

<p1> 7. What is your impression of how the experience should be interacted with over time? (For how long and how many different times) <br><br> </p1>
<p2>
  To give the user a good idea of what is avaliable, with repeat visits to both the site and exhibitions, and allow them to take their time to read up on what interests them <br><br> 
</p2>

<p1> 8. How does the interactive experience communicate how it should be interacted with over time? <br><br> </p1>
<p2>
  Excellently, with simple images that will entice further reading or ticket bookings, where the more you browse the options, the higher chacnc you'll find what you like <br><br> 
</p2>

<p1> 9. What other media forms (digital or otherwise) does the experience reference? <br><br> </p1>
<p2>
  Digital images of real life art peices and places <br>
  Some background videos displaying the art showcases <br><br> 
</p2>

<p1> 10. What does this reference/s communicate to you about how you should act when engaging with your research experience? <br><br> </p1>
<p2>
  Communicates what the website is advertising and what you could expect if you were to attend <br><br> 
</p2> 

<p1> 11. What does this reference/s communicate to you about how you should feel when engaging with your research experience? <br><br> </p1>
<p2>
  If I find an event that appeals to me, I should feel intrigued to go and see the shown exhibition  <br><br> 
</p2>

<p1> 12. What is the most frustrating part of the interaction to you and what makes that part frustrating? <br><br> </p1>
<p2>
  Too many pages, some pages while navigating the site took a while to load and hence dappened my experience <br><br> 
</p2> 

<p1> 13. What is the most satisfying part of the interaction to you and what makes that part satisfying? <br><br> </p1>
<p2>
  The auto scrolling collections and auto playing videos made for a more lively site <br><br> 
</p2>

